{"title_page": "2015 FJ345", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:{{mp|2015 FJ|345}}}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox planet\n | minorplanet     = yes\n | name            = {{mp|2015 FJ|345}}\n | background      = #C2E0FF\n | image           = \n | image_size      = \n | caption         = \n | discovery_ref   = &thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-object\" />\n | discoverer      = [[Mauna Kea Observatories|Mauna Kea Obs.]]\n | discovery_site  = [[Mauna Kea Observatories|Mauna Kea Obs.]]<br />{{small|(first observed only)}}\n | discovered      = 17 March 2015\n | mpc_name        = {{mp|2015 FJ|345}}\n | alt_names       = <!--{{mp|2015 FJ|345}} -->\n | pronounced      = \n | named_after     = \n | mp_category     = {{Hlist\n  | [[Trans-Neptunian object|TNO]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n  | [[Detached object|detached]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"Swiss\" /><ref name=\"Lykawka-2007\" />\n  | [[Scattered disc object|SDO]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" />\n  | [[Distant minor planet|distant]]&thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-object\" />\n  }}\n | orbit_ref       = &thinsp;<ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n | epoch           = 27 April 2019 ([[Julian day|JD]]&nbsp;2458600.5)\n | uncertainty     = {{Hlist\n  | 6\n  | 4<ref name=\"MPC-object\" />\n  }}\n | observation_arc = 1.13&nbsp;[[Julian year (astronomy)|yr]] (413&nbsp;d)\n | aphelion        = 74.837&nbsp;[[Astronomical unit|AU]]\n | perihelion      = 50.785&nbsp;AU\n | semimajor       = 62.811&nbsp;AU\n | eccentricity    = 0.1915\n | period          = 497.81&nbsp;yr (181,824&nbsp;d)\n | mean_anomaly    = 58.879[[Degree (angle)|\u00b0]]\n | mean_motion     = {{Deg2DMS|0.0020|sup=ms}} / day\n | inclination     = 34.973\u00b0\n | asc_node        = 37.881\u00b0\n | arg_peri        = 77.511\u00b0\n | mean_diameter   = {{Ubl\n  | {{val|117|ul=km}}<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" />\n  | {{val|119|u=km}}<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" />\n  | {{val|125|25|u=km}}<ref name=\"Sheppard-2016\" />\n  }}\n | rotation        = \n | albedo          = {{Ubl\n  | 0.08 {{small|(assumed)}}<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" />\n  | 0.09 {{small|(assumed)}}<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" />\n  }}\n | spectral_type   = \n | magnitude       = 25.74<ref name=\"AstDys-object\" />\n | abs_magnitude   = 7.9<ref name=\"MPC-object\" /><ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n}}\n\n'''{{mp|2015 FJ|345}}''' is a [[trans-Neptunian object]] and [[detached object]], located in the [[scattered disc]], the outermost region of the [[Solar System]]. It was first observed on 17 March 2015, by a team led by American astronomer [[Scott Sheppard]] at the [[Mauna Kea Observatories]], Hawaii, United States. With its [[perihelion]] of almost 51&nbsp;AU, it belongs to a small and poorly understood group of very distant objects with moderate eccentricities.<ref name=\"Sheppard-2016\" /><ref name=\"Allen-2006\" /> The object is not a [[List of possible dwarf planets|dwarf planet candidate]] as it only measures approximately {{convert|120|km|mi|abbr=off|sp=us}} in diameter.\n\n== Discovery and naming ==\n\n{{mp|2015 FJ|345}} was first observed on 17 March 2015, by a team of astronomers led by Scott Sheppard of the [[Carnegie Institution for Science]] as part of the survey for distant solar system objects beyond the [[Kuiper Cliff]] using the new wide-field cameras on the [[Subaru Telescope|Subaru]] and [[Cerro Tololo Inter-American Observatory| Cerro Tololo Inter-American Observatory (CTIO)]] telescopes.<ref name=\"Sheppard-2016\" />\n\n== Orbit and classification ==\n[[File:Extreme transneptunian object eccentricity vs perihelion.png|thumb|left|200px|The object is located in the \"gap\", a poorly understood region.]]\n\n{{mp|2015 FJ|345}} orbits the Sun at a distance of 50.8\u201374.8&nbsp;[[Astronomical unit|AU]] once every 497 years and 10 months (181,824 days; [[semi-major axis]] of 62.81&nbsp;AU). Its orbit has an [[orbital eccentricity|eccentricity]] of 0.19 and an [[orbital inclination|inclination]] of 35[[Degree (angle)|\u00b0]] with respect to the [[ecliptic]].<ref name=\"jpldata\" />\n\nThe object belongs to the same group as {{mpl|2004 XR|190}} (\"Buffy\"), {{mpl|2014 FC|72}}, {{mpl|2014 FZ|71}} and {{mpl|2015 KQ|174}} ''(also see diagram)''. With an orbital period of 498 years, it seems to be a [[resonant trans-Neptunian object]]s in a 1:3 [[Orbital resonance|resonance]] with Neptune,<ref name=\"Sheppard-2016\" />{{rp|12}} as several other objects,<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" /> but with a lower eccentricity (0.19 instead of more than 0.60) and higher [[perihelia]] (at 50.8&nbsp;AU rather than 31\u201341&nbsp;AU).\n\nConsidered a [[scattered-disc object|scattered]] and [[detached object]],<ref name=\"Swiss\" /><ref name=\"Lykawka-2007\" /><ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" /> {{mp|2015 FJ|345}} is particularly unusual as it has an unusually circular orbit for a [[scattered-disc object]] (SDO). Although it is thought that traditional scattered-disc objects have been ejected into their current orbits by gravitational interactions with [[Neptune]], the low eccentricity of its orbit and the distance of its perihelion (SDOs generally have highly eccentric orbits and perihelia less than 38&nbsp;AU) seems hard to reconcile with such celestial mechanics. This has led to some uncertainty as to the current theoretical understanding of the outer [[Solar System]]. The theories include close stellar passages, [[Planets beyond Neptune|unseen planet]]/[[rogue planet]]s/[[planetary embryo]]s in the early [[Kuiper belt]], and [[Orbital resonance|resonance]] interaction with an [[Formation and evolution of the Solar System#Planetary migration|outward]]-[[Planetary migration|migrating Neptune]]. The [[Kozai mechanism]] is capable of transferring orbital eccentricity to a higher inclination.<ref name=\"Allen-2006\" />\n\n== Physical characteristics ==\n\n{{mp|2015 FJ|345}} has a diameter estimated between 117 and 125 kilometers,<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\" /><ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" /><ref name=\"Sheppard-2016\" /> roughly a quarter the size of {{mpl|2004 XR|190}} (\"Buffy\"), which is estimated at around {{convert|500|km|mi}}, roughly a quarter the size of [[Pluto]]. It is therefore not a [[List of possible dwarf planets|dwarf planet candidate]].<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"jpldata\">{{cite web\n  |type       = 2016-05-03 last obs.\n  |title      = JPL Small-Body Database Browser: (2015 FJ345)\n  |url        = https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=3753792\n  |publisher  = [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate = 12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-object\">{{cite web\n  |title      = 2015 FJ345\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=2015+FJ345\n  |accessdate = 12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AstDys-object\">{{cite web\n  |title      = 2015 FJ345 \u2013 Ephemerides\n  |publisher  = AstDyS-2, Asteroids{{Snd}} Dynamic Site, Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy\n  |url        = https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.0&n=2015FJ345\n  |accessdate = 12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"johnstonsarchive-TNO-list\">{{cite web\n  |title      = List of Known Trans-Neptunian Objects\n  |work       = Johnston's Archive\n  |date       = 7 October 2018\n  |last       = Johnston |first= Wm. Robert\n  |url        = http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/astro/tnoslist.html\n  |accessdate = 12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\">{{cite web\n  |title      = How many dwarf planets are there in the outer solar system?\n  |publisher  = [[California Institute of Technology]]\n  |last       = Brown |first= Michael E.\n  |url        = http://web.gps.caltech.edu/~mbrown/dps.html\n  |accessdate = 12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Swiss\">Jewitt, David, Morbidelli, Alessandro, & Rauer, Heike. (2007). ''Trans-Neptunian Objects and Comets: Saas-Fee Advanced Course 35. Swis