{"title_page": "List of Grand Slam men's singles champions", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\nThis article details the list of men's singles [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournaments [[tennis]] champions. Some major changes have taken place in history and have affected the number of titles that have been won by various players. These have included the opening of the French national championships to international players in 1925, the elimination of the challenge round in 1922, and the admission of professional players in 1968 (the start of the [[History of tennis#Open era|Open era]]).<ref>ESPN Sports Almanac 2006, page 814</ref><ref>World Book Encyclopedia 2008 T p166a</ref><ref>Compton Encyclopedia 1975 ST p301</ref><ref>Concord Encyclopedia</ref><ref>CBS Sports \"[http://www.cbssports.com/tennis/history/slams/women]\"</ref><ref>Top End Sports \"[http://www.topendsports.com/events/tennis-grand-slam/]\"</ref><ref>USA Today Tennis \"[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/tennis/00wim/sampras2.htm]\"</ref><ref>Tennis 28 Slams \"[http://www.tennis28.com/slams/wins_alltime.html]\"</ref>\n\nNote:  All of these tournaments have been listed since they began, rather than when they officially became majors. The Australian and US tournaments have only been officially regarded as majors by the ILTF (now the ITF) since 1924 (though many regarded the US Championships as a major before then). The French Championships have only been a major since 1925 (when it became open to all amateurs internationally).\nBefore 1924 (since 1912/1913 to 1923) there were 3 official majors: Wimbledon, the [[World Hard Court Championships]] (played on [[clay court|clay]]) and the [[World Covered Court Championships]] (played on an indoor wood surface).\n[[Image:Roger Federer (26 June 2009, Wimbledon) 3 cropped.jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Roger Federer]] has won [[Grand Slam (tennis)|20 Major singles titles]] \u2014 the most by any man in history, including an all-time record eight [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] titles.</center>]]\n[[Image:Rodney George Laver.jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Rod Laver]] is the only man in history to win all four Majors in the same calendar year \"The Grand Slam\" twice (1962 and 1969)</center>]]\n[[Image:Don Budge.jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Don Budge]] is the only male player in tennis history to have won six consecutive Grand Slam singles titles, from [[1937 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|Wimbledon 1937]] to [[1938 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|U.S. Championships 1938]].</center>]]\n[[File:Paris-FR-75-open de tennis-2-6--17-Roland Garros-Rafael Nadal-21.jpg|thumb|<center>[[Rafael Nadal]] has won 19 Major titles, including 12 [[French Open]] titles at [[Stade Roland Garros|Roland Garros]], making him the only male player with double digit titles at one particular Grand Slam event.</center>]]\n[[File:Novak Djokovic French Open 2015.jpg|thumb|<center>[[Novak Djokovic]] is the only player to hold all four major titles on three different surfaces simultaneously. He has 17 major titles and he holds the all-time record of 8 [[Australian Open]] titles.</center>]]\n[[File:Pete Sampras.jpg|thumb|<center>[[Pete Sampras]] won 14 Major titles, 7 of them at Wimbledon. 14 Major titles was the world record at the time of his retirement in 2002.</center>]]\n[[Image:Bill Tilden in color.jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Bill Tilden]] won 10 Major titles in the 1920s, becoming the first male player to achieve this feat.</center>]]\n[[Image:Ken Rosewall (1970).jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Ken Rosewall]] holds a record 15 [[Major professional tennis tournaments before the Open Era|Pro Slam]] titles, and a record 23 overall Major titles, counting both Amateur and Pro circuits.</center>]]\n[[Image:Roy Emerson \u2013 Tennis te Hilversum Nummer 4 en 5 Spelmomenten, Bestanddeelnr 915-3864.jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Roy Emerson]] was the first male player in history to win each Major title twice, and the only player to have won a career Grand Slam in both singles and doubles.</center>]]\n[[Image:Andre Agassi Indian Wells 2006.jpg|thumb|right|<center>[[Andre Agassi]] was the first male player to complete the Career Grand Slam on three different surfaces, and the first male player in history to win the Career Golden Slam (winning the four Grand Slams and the Olympic Gold Medal in singles).</center>]]\n\n== Champions by year ==\n\n{| width=53%\n| valign=top width=33% align=left |\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n|'''Flag Icon Key'''\n|-\n| [[List of IOC country codes|List of National Flags]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n|-\n!Year !! style=\"width:25%\"|[[List of Australian Open men's singles champions|Australian Open]] !! style=\"width:25%\"|[[List of French Open men's singles champions|French Open]] !! style=\"width:25%\"|[[List of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon]] !! style=\"width:25%\"|[[List of US Open men's singles champions|US Open]]\n|-\n|'''1877'''||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>started in 1905</small>||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>started in 1891</small>||{{flagicon|UK}} [[Spencer Gore (sportsman)|Spencer Gore]]||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>started in 1881</small>\n|-\n|'''1878'''||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>''tournament not created''</small>||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>''tournament not created''</small>||{{flagicon|UK}} [[Frank Hadow]]||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>''tournament not created''</small>\n|-\n|'''1879'''||style=\"background:#ececec;color:gray;text-align:center\" class=\"table-na\"|<small>''tournament not created''</small>||style=\"back