{"title_page": "Yasmeen Lari", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n'''Yasmeen Lari''' (born c. 1941; {{lang-ur|\u06cc\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u0644\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}) is Pakistan's first female architect.<ref>[http://lumiere.lib.vt.edu/iawa_db/view_all.php3?person_pk=31&region=134&subregion=&table=bio&cSel=134 \"Yasmeen Lari\"], ''International Archive of Women in Architecture''. Retrieved 27 February 2012.</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> She is best known for her involvement in the intersection of architecture and social justice. Since her official retirement from architectural practice in 2000, her UN-recognized NGO Heritage Foundation Pakistan has been taking on humanitarian relief work and historical conservation projects in rural villages all around Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/apr/01/yasmeen-lari-pakistan-architect-first-female-jane-drew |title=The barefoot architect: 'I was a starchitect for 36 years. Now I'm atoning' |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Oliver Wainwright |date= 1 April 2020}}</ref> She was awarded with the prestigious [[Fukuoka Prize]] in 2016.\n\n==Early life==\n\nYasmeen Lari was born in the town of [[Dera Ghazi Khan]] and spent her early years in and around [[Lahore]] in a renowned clan of [[Iraqi Biradari]]. Her father Zafarul Ahsan, an ICS officer, was working on major development projects in Lahore and other cities, through which Lari was exposed to architecture. Her sister is Pakistani politician [[Nasreen Jalil]]. When she was 15 years old, she first left Pakistan to go to London with her family.<ref name=\":2\" /> Initially there for a vacation, she and her siblings ended up enrolling in school in London.<ref name=\":2\" /> Upon her rejection from architecture school, Yasmeen Lari studied two years of arts in London before being accepted into the [[School of Architecture, Oxford Brookes University|Oxford Brookes University School of Architecture]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from the Oxford School of Architecture in 1964, Lari returned to Pakistan at 23 with her husband, Suhail Zaheer Lari, and opened her architecture firm Lari Associates in [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], Pakistan.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = Women of Pakistan - Yasmeen Lari|url = http://kazbar.org/jazbah/yasmeen.php|website = Jazbah Magazine|accessdate = 2015-10-26|date = 2008|last = Kazmi|first = Laila|publisher = Jazbah}}</ref> She became the first female architect in Pakistan. Initially, she faced difficulties when workers at construction sites challenged her authority or knowledge because of her gender.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iftekhar|first1=Anadil|title=The Queen of Architecture|url=http://magazine.thenews.com.pk/mag/detail_article.asp?magId=1&id=5401|website=You! The New Woman Lifestyle|publisher=Jang Group of Newspapers|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Lari became an elected Member of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (RIBA).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Yasmeen Lari|url = http://archnet.org/authorities/39|website = ArchNet|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref>\n\nHer later projects included housing, such as the Angoori Bagh Housing (ABH) (1978), and commercial buildings, such as the [[Taj Mahal Hotel (Karachi)|Taj Mahal Hotel]] in 1981, the Finance and Trade Center in 1989, and the Pakistan State Oil House (PSO Company headquarters) in Karachi in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLari retired in 2000 from architectural practice.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.dwell.com/interviews/article/qa-pakistans-first-female-architect|title = Q&A with Pakistan's First Female Architect|date = 2 July 2012|accessdate = 27 August 2014|website = Dwell|publisher = Dwell Media LLC|last = Gillin|first = Jaime}}</ref> However, she remains active with her historical preservation by serving as the advisor of the [[UNESCO]] project, as the executive director of Heritage Foundation Pakistan, and as the chairperson of the Karavan Initiatives.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBetween 2010 and 2014, among other projects Lari had built over 36,000 houses for those affected by Pakistan's floods and earthquakes. Lari implements traditional building techniques and local materials in rebuilding the Sindh Valley region of Pakistan.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.archdaily.com/541222/al-jazeera-s-rebel-architecture-episode-2-the-traditional-future/|title = Al Jazeera's Rebel Architecture: Episode 2, \"The Traditional Future\"|date = 26 August 2014|accessdate = 27 August 2014|website = ArchDaily.com|publisher = Al Jazeera|last = Watkins|first = Katie}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she helped villagers in [[Awaran District]] who were hit by the [[2013 Balochistan earthquake]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Design philosophy ==\nOn architectural practice in Southeast Asia, Lari has said, \"The two ends of the spectrum of the two worlds we live and work in are best captured in the words of two famous architects, Mies van der Rohe and Hassan Fathy. Mies van der Rohe, a master of putting the elements of a building together and the grand master of detail, has said: \"I am first interested in a good building. Then I place it in the best possible spot.' In contrast Hassan Fathy, who has spoken more forcefully than any other on the beatify of the vernacular and the importance of tradition, states: 'You must start from the beginning, letting your new buildings grow from the daily lives of the people who will live in them, shaping the houses to the measure of people's songs, weaving the pattern of a village as if on the village looms, mindful of the trees and the crafts that grow there, respectful of the skylines and humble before the seasons.'\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/48041242|title=An emancipated place : the proceedings of the conference and exhibition held in Mumbai, February 2000 : women in architecture, 2000 plus : a conference on the work of women architects : focus South Asia|date=2000|publisher=Hecar Foundation|others=Somaya, Brinda., Mehta, Urvashi., Hecar Foundation.|isbn=8175251948|location=Mumbai|oclc=48041242}}</ref>\n\n==Architectural work==\n\n=== Completed projects ===\n* Naval Officers Housing, Karachi<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = Yasmeen Lari: The Architect and the Saviour|url = https://nustscienceblog.wordpress.com/2015/05/08/yasmeen-lari-the-architect-and-the-saviour/|website = NUST Science|accessdate = 2015-10-27|last = Kaleem|first = Ayesha}}</ref>\n* Angoori Bagh Housing (also known as ABH) (1978)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Taj Mahal Hotel, Karachi (1981)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Finance and Trade Center (FTC Building), Karachi (1989)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Pakistan State Oil House (PSO House), Karachi (1991)<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Historical conservation and restoration projects (incomplete) ===\n* Khairpur Heritage Centre<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/759973/fighting-on-different-fronts|title=Fighting on different fronts|last=Noorani|first=Asif|date=2012-10-29|website=Dawn|access-date=2016-04-30}}</ref>\n* Sethi house in [[Sethi Mohallah]] (2010\u20132012)<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Bibliography==\n\nSome of Yasmeen Lari's publications include:\n\n*''Slums and Squatter Settlements: Their Role and Improvement Strategy''\n*''Our Heritage in Muslim Architecture''\n*''Tharparkar and Sialkot after the War''\n*1993 ''\u2013 Traditional Architecture of Thatta''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Traditional Architecture of Thatta|url = https://www.academia.edu/3615261/Traditional_Architecture_of_Thatta|website = www.academia.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref>\n* 1997 \u2013 ''The Dual City: Karachi During the Raj (''co-authored'' with her son, Mihail Lari)''<ref name=\":4\" />\n* 1997 \u2013 ''The Jewel of Sindh: Samma Tombs on the Makli Hill'' ''(co-authored with her husband, Suhail Zaheer Lari)''<ref name=\":4\" /> \n* 2001 \u2013 ''Karachi: Illustrated City Guide (photography by her husband, Suhail Zaheer Lari)''\n* 2003 \u2013 ''Lahore: Illustrated City Guide''\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2002, the [[Heritage Foundation Pakistan|Heritage Foundation]] received the U.N. Recognition Award from the [[United Nations]] for its efforts and results to promote cultural and historical conservation.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2006, Lari was awarded the ''Sitara-e-Imtiaz'', one of the highest civil awards by the [[Government of Pakistan]], in recognition of her services to the architectural profession and to heritage conservation of historical sites in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.heritagefoundationpak.org/Page/1307/About-Us--Registration--Mission--Vision--Board-of-Directors-HF-Offices-Registration-Heritage-Foundat|title = About us|date = |accessdate = 27 August 2014|website = heritagefoundationpak.org|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she received the Pakistani \"1st Wonder Women of the Year Award\".<ref>[http://www.wonderwomenpakistan.com/1st_edition.php ''Wonderwomen of the Year Awards'']. Retrieved 27 February 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she received the [[Fukuoka Prize]] for Arts & Culture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fukuoka-prize.org/en/laureate/prize/cul/yasumlari.php|title=Laureates, Yasmeen LARI|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=Fukuoka Prize|language=ja-JP|access-date=2017-01-11|via=}}</ref>\n\nShe has been awarded [[Jane Drew Prize]] 2020, raising the profile of women in architecture and design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2020/01/30/yasmeen-lari-jane-drew-prize-2020/|title=Pakistani architect Yasmeen Lari wins the Jane Drew Prize 2020|date=2020-01-30|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nYasmeen Lari lives in Karachi, Pakistan with her husband, Suhail Lari. She has three children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www2.arch.uiuc.edu/organizations/wia/archtspotl/lariyasmeen.html Women In Architecture]\n*{{cite book|url=http://www.thehecarfoundation.org/publications.html|title=An Emancipated Place, Women in Architecture - 2000 PLUS: The proceedings of the conference and exhibition held in Mumai, February 2000|last=|first=|date=February 2000|publisher=The HECAR Foundation|year=|isbn=81-7525-194-8|editor1-last=Somaya|editor1-first=Brinda|location=Mumbai, India|pages=20\u201328|accessdate=30 September 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lari, Yasmeen}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani architects]]\n[[Category:Architects from Lahore]]\n[[Category:Pakistani women architects]]\n[[Category:Pakistani architectural historians]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Iraqi descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani women writers]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:Architects from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Sitara-i-Imtiaz]]\n[[Category:Women historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n'''Yasmeen Lari''' (born c. 1941; {{lang-ur|\u06cc\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u0644\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}) is Pakistan's first female architect.<ref>[http://lumiere.lib.vt.edu/iawa_db/view_all.php3?person_pk=31&region=134&subregion=&table=bio&cSel=134 \"Yasmeen Lari\"], ''International Archive of Women in Architecture''. Retrieved 27 February 2012.</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> She is best known for her involvement in the intersection of architecture and social justice. Since her official retirement from architectural practice in 2000, her UN-recognized NGO Heritage Foundation Pakistan has been taking on humanitarian relief work and historical conservation projects in rural villages all around Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/apr/01/yasmeen-lari-pakistan-architect-first-female-jane-drew |title=The barefoot architect: 'I was a starchitect for 36 years. Now I'm atoning' |newspaper=The Guardian |date=  |author=Oliver Wainwright |date= 1 April 2020}}</ref> She was awarded with the prestigious [[Fukuoka Prize]] in 2016.\n\n==Early life==\n\nYasmeen Lari was born in the town of [[Dera Ghazi Khan]] and spent her early years in and around [[Lahore]] in a renowned clan of [[Iraqi Biradari]]. Her father Zafarul Ahsan, an ICS officer, was working on major development projects in Lahore and other cities, through which Lari was exposed to architecture. Her sister is Pakistani politician [[Nasreen Jalil]]. When she was 15 years old, she first left Pakistan to go to London with her family.<ref name=\":2\" /> Initially there for a vacation, she and her siblings ended up enrolling in school in London.<ref name=\":2\" /> Upon her rejection from architecture school, Yasmeen Lari studied two years of arts in London before being accepted into the [[School of Architecture, Oxford Brookes University|Oxford Brookes University School of Architecture]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from the Oxford School of Architecture in 1964, Lari returned to Pakistan at 23 with her husband, Suhail Zaheer Lari, and opened her architecture firm Lari Associates in [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], Pakistan.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = Women of Pakistan - Yasmeen Lari|url = http://kazbar.org/jazbah/yasmeen.php|website = Jazbah Magazine|accessdate = 2015-10-26|date = 2008|last = Kazmi|first = Laila|publisher = Jazbah}}</ref> She became the first female architect in Pakistan. Initially, she faced difficulties when workers at construction sites challenged her authority or knowledge because of her gender.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iftekhar|first1=Anadil|title=The Queen of Architecture|url=http://magazine.thenews.com.pk/mag/detail_article.asp?magId=1&id=5401|website=You! The New Woman Lifestyle|publisher=Jang Group of Newspapers|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Lari became an elected Member of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (RIBA).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Yasmeen Lari|url = http://archnet.org/authorities/39|website = ArchNet|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref>\n\nHer later projects included housing, such as the Angoori Bagh Housing (ABH) (1978), and commercial buildings, such as the [[Taj Mahal Hotel (Karachi)|Taj Mahal Hotel]] in 1981, the Finance and Trade Center in 1989, and the Pakistan State Oil House (PSO Company headquarters) in Karachi in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLari retired in 2000 from architectural practice.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.dwell.com/interviews/article/qa-pakistans-first-female-architect|title = Q&A with Pakistan's First Female Architect|date = 2 July 2012|accessdate = 27 August 2014|website = Dwell|publisher = Dwell Media LLC|last = Gillin|first = Jaime}}</ref> However, she remains active with her historical preservation by serving as the advisor of the [[UNESCO]] project, as the executive director of Heritage Foundation Pakistan, and as the chairperson of the Karavan Initiatives.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBetween 2010 and 2014, among other projects Lari had built over 36,000 houses for those affected by Pakistan's floods and earthquakes. Lari implements traditional building techniques and local materials in rebuilding the Sindh Valley region of Pakistan.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.archdaily.com/541222/al-jazeera-s-rebel-architecture-episode-2-the-traditional-future/|title = Al Jazeera's Rebel Architecture: Episode 2, \"The Traditional Future\"|date = 26 August 2014|accessdate = 27 August 2014|website = ArchDaily.com|publisher = Al Jazeera|last = Watkins|first = Katie}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she helped villagers in [[Awaran District]] who were hit by the [[2013 Balochistan earthquake]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Design philosophy ==\nOn architectural practice in Southeast Asia, Lari has said, \"The two ends of the spectrum of the two worlds we live and work in are best captured in the words of two famous architects, Mies van der Rohe and Hassan Fathy. Mies van der Rohe, a master of putting the elements of a building together and the grand master of detail, has said: \"I am first interested in a good building. Then I place it in the best possible spot.' In contrast Hassan Fathy, who has spoken more forcefully than any other on the beatify of the vernacular and the importance of tradition, states: 'You must start from the beginning, letting your new buildings grow from the daily lives of the people who will live in them, shaping the houses to the measure of people's songs, weaving the pattern of a village as if on the village looms, mindful of the trees and the crafts that grow there, respectful of the skylines and humble before the seasons.'\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/48041242|title=An emancipated place : the proceedings of the conference and exhibition held in Mumbai, February 2000 : women in architecture, 2000 plus : a conference on the work of women architects : focus South Asia|date=2000|publisher=Hecar Foundation|others=Somaya, Brinda., Mehta, Urvashi., Hecar Foundation.|isbn=8175251948|location=Mumbai|oclc=48041242}}</ref>\n\n==Architectural work==\n\n=== Completed projects ===\n* Naval Officers Housing, Karachi<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = Yasmeen Lari: The Architect and the Saviour|url = https://nustscienceblog.wordpress.com/2015/05/08/yasmeen-lari-the-architect-and-the-saviour/|website = NUST Science|accessdate = 2015-10-27|last = Kaleem|first = Ayesha}}</ref>\n* Angoori Bagh Housing (also known as ABH) (1978)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Taj Mahal Hotel, Karachi (1981)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Finance and Trade Center (FTC Building), Karachi (1989)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Pakistan State Oil House (PSO House), Karachi (1991)<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Historical conservation and restoration projects (incomplete) ===\n* Khairpur Heritage Centre<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/759973/fighting-on-different-fronts|title=Fighting on different fronts|last=Noorani|first=Asif|date=2012-10-29|website=Dawn|access-date=2016-04-30}}</ref>\n* Sethi house in [[Sethi Mohallah]] (2010\u20132012)<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Bibliography==\n\nSome of Yasmeen Lari's publications include:\n\n*''Slums and Squatter Settlements: Their Role and Improvement Strategy''\n*''Our Heritage in Muslim Architecture''\n*''Tharparkar and Sialkot after the War''\n*1993 ''\u2013 Traditional Architecture of Thatta''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Traditional Architecture of Thatta|url = https://www.academia.edu/3615261/Traditional_Architecture_of_Thatta|website = www.academia.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref>\n* 1997 \u2013 ''The Dual City: Karachi During the Raj (''co-authored'' with her son, Mihail Lari)''<ref name=\":4\" />\n* 1997 \u2013 ''The Jewel of Sindh: Samma Tombs on the Makli Hill'' ''(co-authored with her husband, Suhail Zaheer Lari)''<ref name=\":4\" /> \n* 2001 \u2013 ''Karachi: Illustrated City Guide (photography by her husband, Suhail Zaheer Lari)''\n* 2003 \u2013 ''Lahore: Illustrated City Guide''\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2002, the [[Heritage Foundation Pakistan|Heritage Foundation]] received the U.N. Recognition Award from the [[United Nations]] for its efforts and results to promote cultural and historical conservation.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2006, Lari was awarded the ''Sitara-e-Imtiaz'', one of the highest civil awards by the [[Government of Pakistan]], in recognition of her services to the architectural profession and to heritage conservation of historical sites in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.heritagefoundationpak.org/Page/1307/About-Us--Registration--Mission--Vision--Board-of-Directors-HF-Offices-Registration-Heritage-Foundat|title = About us|date = |accessdate = 27 August 2014|website = heritagefoundationpak.org|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she received the Pakistani \"1st Wonder Women of the Year Award\".<ref>[http://www.wonderwomenpakistan.com/1st_edition.php ''Wonderwomen of the Year Awards'']. Retrieved 27 February 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she received the [[Fukuoka Prize]] for Arts & Culture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fukuoka-prize.org/en/laureate/prize/cul/yasumlari.php|title=Laureates, Yasmeen LARI|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=Fukuoka Prize|language=ja-JP|access-date=2017-01-11|via=}}</ref>\n\nShe has been awarded [[Jane Drew Prize]] 2020, raising the profile of women in architecture and design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2020/01/30/yasmeen-lari-jane-drew-prize-2020/|title=Pakistani architect Yasmeen Lari wins the Jane Drew Prize 2020|date=2020-01-30|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nYasmeen Lari lives in Karachi, Pakistan with her husband, Suhail Lari. She has three children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www2.arch.uiuc.edu/organizations/wia/archtspotl/lariyasmeen.html Women In Architecture]\n*{{cite book|url=http://www.thehecarfoundation.org/publications.html|title=An Emancipated Place, Women in Architecture - 2000 PLUS: The proceedings of the conference and exhibition held in Mumai, February 2000|last=|first=|date=February 2000|publisher=The HECAR Foundation|year=|isbn=81-7525-194-8|editor1-last=Somaya|editor1-first=Brinda|location=Mumbai, India|pages=20\u201328|accessdate=30 September 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lari, Yasmeen}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani architects]]\n[[Category:Architects from Lahore]]\n[[Category:Pakistani women architects]]\n[[Category:Pakistani architectural historians]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Iraqi descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani women writers]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:Architects from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Sitara-i-Imtiaz]]\n[[Category:Women historians]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yasmeen_Lari"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in West Virginia, United States}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia\n| width           = \n| image           = West Virginia National Guard (49667643407).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Members of the [[West Virginia National Guard]] provide personal protective equipment training on March 16, 2020\n| map1            = COVID-19 In West Virginia County Map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed COVID-19 cases in West Virginia as of March 26th, 2020\n{{legend|#ff0000| Confirmed Cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[West Virginia]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]]\n| arrival_date    = March 17, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 162<ref name=\"WVDHHS\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19/Pages/default.aspx |publisher=West Virginia Department of Health and Human Services |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 1\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19}}\n}}\n\nThe U.S. state of [[West Virginia]] reported its first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on March 17, 2020, becoming the last state in the [[United States]] to do so.<ref name=cbspittsburgh>{{cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-in-west-virginia-state-reports-first-positive-covid-19-case/ |title=Coronavirus In West Virginia: State Reports First Positive COVID-19 Case|publisher=CBS Pittsburgh|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020 the state reported its first COVID-19 death.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/West Virginia medical cases chart}}\nAs of March 16, the state had tested 84 suspected cases.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Wines|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/us/weve-got-a-monster-thats-looming-west-virginia-is-the-last-state-without-a-coronavirus-case.html|title='We've Got a Monster That's Looming': West Virginia Is the Last State Without a Coronavirus Case|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-17|last2=Robertson|first2=Campbell|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> West Virginia announced its first case, in [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]], on March 17, 2020.<ref name=\"wowktv\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wowktv.com/news/west-virginia/covid-19-confirmed-in-west-virginia/|title=COVID-19 confirmed in West Virginia|date=March 17, 2020|website=WOWK 13 News|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wsaz\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=McGuire|first=Colin|date=March 18, 2020|title=First confirmed WV Coronavirus case in Shepherdstown, wife to get tested|url=https://www.journal-news.net/journal-news/first-confirmed-wv-coronavirus-case-in-shepherdstown-wife-to-get/article_3033c813-4675-58a1-b127-d91fc97e1178.html|newspaper=The Journal|location=Martinsburg, West Virginia|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the second case was announced. Also on that date, 148 West Virginians had been tested for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/18/second-coronavirus-case-in-west-virginia-confirmed/|title=2nd coronavirus case in West Virginia confirmed|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-19|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 20, West Virginia had confirmed 8 cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/20/eighth-coronavirus-case-confirmed-first-case-recognized-in-kanawha-county/|title=Eighth coronavirus case confirmed; first case recognized in Kanawha County|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-20|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 22, there were 16 confirmed cases.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\nA March 22 [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]] article described efforts to implement [[social distancing]] in [[Grant County, West Virginia|Grant County]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frankel |first1=Todd |title=In pro-Trump West Virginia, a fight to convince residents a pandemic is coming |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/22/pro-trump-west-virginia-fight-convince-residents-pandemic-is-coming/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 13, Governor [[Jim Justice]] announced all schools across the state would close beginning on March 16, 2020 for an indefinite period of time as a proactive measure.<ref name=wsaz2>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |title=W.Va. Gov. Justice closing state schools indefinitely |last=Tierney |first=Brendan |date=March 13, 2020 |website=[[WSAZ-TV]] |language=english |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314093424/https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the mayor of [[Charleston, West Virginia]], declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvpublic.org/post/charleston-wva-declares-state-emergency-part-coronavirus-response|title=Charleston, W.Va. Declares State Of Emergency As Part Of Coronavirus Response|last=Mistich|first=Dave|date=2020-03-15|website=[[West Virginia Public Broadcasting]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Governor Justice declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-west-virginia-only-state-no-case-ac32ce6d-5523-4310-a219-7d1d1dcb6b44.html|title=West Virginia, the only U.S. state with no reported coronavirus cases, declares emergency|last=Falconer|first=Rebecca|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Justice ordered restaurant dining rooms, bars, and casinos to close until March 31.<ref name=\"wsaz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Gov-Jim-Justice-confirms-case-of-COVID-19-in-West-Virginia-568875791.html |title=Gov. Jim Justice confirms case of COVID-19 in West Virginia|publisher= WSAZ|date= March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, several Mid-Ohio Valley counties had closed their courthouses to the public or limited access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/mid-ohio-valley-counties-limiting-access-to-courthouses/|title=Mid-Ohio Valley counties limiting access to courthouses|last=Black|first=Candice|date=2020-03-21|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nBy March 22, Justice urged West Virginians to [[Stay-at-home order|stay home]] as much as possible.<ref name=\"March 22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/justice-not-ready-to-close-west-virginia-as-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-12/|title=Justice not ready to close West Virginia as coronavirus cases grow to 12|last=Adams|first=Steven Allen|date=March 22, 2020|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Justice was joined by Dr. [[Clay Marsh]], vice president of [[West Virginia University]] and executive dean for Health Sciences. Marsh said that New York is being hit by a tsunami wave of coronavirus cases and if West Virginia can stay home as much as possible the next few weeks, the tsunami wave can become more like a stream for West Virginia.<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\n\u201cWe are faced with a pandemic by a virus that we have no immune system that responds to, so we can\u2019t fight it ... If we do these things, we\u2019ll continue to be the leaders. We have demonstrated how we too, as a state pulling together, can protect each other and protect our health care workers. Once this window of opportunity is gone, it won\u2019t matter what we do then.\u201d<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Justice ordered non-essential businesses to be closed immediately, and issued a [[stay-at-home order]] effective March 24 at 8 p.m.<ref name=\"WBOY March 23\">{{cite web |title=WATCH LIVE: WV Gov. Justice announces stay at home order during virtual news briefing on COVID-19 |url=https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |publisher=[[WBOY-TV]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323183355/https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |archivedate=March 23, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Justice orders shutdown of non-essential businesses in West Virginia; first community-transmitted case has been confirmed |url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/gov-justice-orders-shutdown-of-non-essential-businesses-in-west/article_24910f48-6d21-11ea-8518-3fbb944964d3.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=West Virginia's News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, WV Statewide Day of Prayer, a 45-minute service dedicated to the people affected with Coronavirus disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvnstv.com/video/wv-statewide-day-of-prayer-service/4428831/|title=WV Statewide Day of Prayer Service|website=WVNS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> It was held by Governor Jim Justice and moderator Dr. Dan Anderson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.wv.gov/News/press-releases/2020/Pages/Gov.-Justice,-religious-leaders-to-hold-virtual-statewide-Day-of-Prayer-service-tomorrow-at-noon.aspx|title=Gov. Justice, religious leaders to hold virtual statewide Day of Prayer service tomorrow at noon.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal response ===\nWest Virginia will receive $5.6 million of federal money to fight COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/senators-west-virginia-to-receive-nearly-million-for-covid-/article_84856dbd-0431-5122-a3ef-cdcc2d33da0e.html Senators: West Virginia to receive nearly $5.6 million for COVID-19 response] WV News, March 17, 2020</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships|publisher= NCAA|date= March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title= NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak| publisher= MLive.com|date= March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19 Information] from the West Virginia Department of Health & Human Resources\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|United States|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Disasters in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Health in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:2020 in West Virginia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia\n| width           = \n| image           = West Virginia National Guard (49667643407).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Members of the [[West Virginia National Guard]] provide personal protective equipment training on March 16, 2020\n| map1            = COVID-19 In West Virginia County Map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed COVID-19 cases in West Virginia as of March 26th, 2020\n{{legend|#ff0000| Confirmed Cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[West Virginia]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]]\n| arrival_date    = March 17, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 162<ref name=\"WVDHHS\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19/Pages/default.aspx |publisher=West Virginia Department of Health and Human Services |accessdate=April 1st, 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 1\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19}}\n}}\n\nThe U.S. state of [[West Virginia]] reported its first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on March 17, 2020, becoming the last state in the [[United States]] to do so.<ref name=cbspittsburgh>{{cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-in-west-virginia-state-reports-first-positive-covid-19-case/ |title=Coronavirus In West Virginia: State Reports First Positive COVID-19 Case|publisher=CBS Pittsburgh|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020 the state reported its first COVID-19 death.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/West Virginia medical cases chart}}\nAs of March 16, the state had tested 84 suspected cases.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Wines|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/us/weve-got-a-monster-thats-looming-west-virginia-is-the-last-state-without-a-coronavirus-case.html|title='We've Got a Monster That's Looming': West Virginia Is the Last State Without a Coronavirus Case|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-17|last2=Robertson|first2=Campbell|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> West Virginia announced its first case, in [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]], on March 17, 2020.<ref name=\"wowktv\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wowktv.com/news/west-virginia/covid-19-confirmed-in-west-virginia/|title=COVID-19 confirmed in West Virginia|date=March 17, 2020|website=WOWK 13 News|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wsaz\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=McGuire|first=Colin|date=March 18, 2020|title=First confirmed WV Coronavirus case in Shepherdstown, wife to get tested|url=https://www.journal-news.net/journal-news/first-confirmed-wv-coronavirus-case-in-shepherdstown-wife-to-get/article_3033c813-4675-58a1-b127-d91fc97e1178.html|newspaper=The Journal|location=Martinsburg, West Virginia|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the second case was announced. Also on that date, 148 West Virginians had been tested for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/18/second-coronavirus-case-in-west-virginia-confirmed/|title=2nd coronavirus case in West Virginia confirmed|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-19|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 20, West Virginia had confirmed 8 cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/20/eighth-coronavirus-case-confirmed-first-case-recognized-in-kanawha-county/|title=Eighth coronavirus case confirmed; first case recognized in Kanawha County|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-20|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 22, there were 16 confirmed cases.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\nA March 22 [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]] article described efforts to implement [[social distancing]] in [[Grant County, West Virginia|Grant County]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frankel |first1=Todd |title=In pro-Trump West Virginia, a fight to convince residents a pandemic is coming |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/22/pro-trump-west-virginia-fight-convince-residents-pandemic-is-coming/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 13, Governor [[Jim Justice]] announced all schools across the state would close beginning on March 16, 2020 for an indefinite period of time as a proactive measure.<ref name=wsaz2>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |title=W.Va. Gov. Justice closing state schools indefinitely |last=Tierney |first=Brendan |date=March 13, 2020 |website=[[WSAZ-TV]] |language=english |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314093424/https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the mayor of [[Charleston, West Virginia]], declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvpublic.org/post/charleston-wva-declares-state-emergency-part-coronavirus-response|title=Charleston, W.Va. Declares State Of Emergency As Part Of Coronavirus Response|last=Mistich|first=Dave|date=2020-03-15|website=[[West Virginia Public Broadcasting]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 16, Governor Justice declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-west-virginia-only-state-no-case-ac32ce6d-5523-4310-a219-7d1d1dcb6b44.html|title=West Virginia, the only U.S. state with no reported coronavirus cases, declares emergency|last=Falconer|first=Rebecca|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> \n\nOn March 17, Justice ordered restaurant dining rooms, bars, and casinos to close until March 31.<ref name=\"wsaz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Gov-Jim-Justice-confirms-case-of-COVID-19-in-West-Virginia-568875791.html |title=Gov. Jim Justice confirms case of COVID-19 in West Virginia|publisher= WSAZ|date= March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, several Mid-Ohio Valley counties had closed their courthouses to the public or limited access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/mid-ohio-valley-counties-limiting-access-to-courthouses/|title=Mid-Ohio Valley counties limiting access to courthouses|last=Black|first=Candice|date=2020-03-21|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nBy March 22, Justice urged West Virginians to [[Stay-at-home order|stay home]] as much as possible.<ref name=\"March 22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/justice-not-ready-to-close-west-virginia-as-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-12/|title=Justice not ready to close West Virginia as coronavirus cases grow to 12|last=Adams|first=Steven Allen|date=March 22, 2020|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Justice was joined by Dr. [[Clay Marsh]], vice president of [[West Virginia University]] and executive dean for Health Sciences. Marsh said that New York is being hit by a tsunami wave of coronavirus cases and if West Virginia can stay home as much as possible the next few weeks, the tsunami wave can become more like a stream for West Virginia.<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\n\u201cWe are faced with a pandemic by a virus that we have no immune system that responds to, so we can\u2019t fight it ... If we do these things, we\u2019ll continue to be the leaders. We have demonstrated how we too, as a state pulling together, can protect each other and protect our health care workers. Once this window of opportunity is gone, it won\u2019t matter what we do then.\u201d<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Justice ordered non-essential businesses to be closed immediately, and issued a [[stay-at-home order]] effective March 24 at 8 p.m.<ref name=\"WBOY March 23\">{{cite web |title=WATCH LIVE: WV Gov. Justice announces stay at home order during virtual news briefing on COVID-19 |url=https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |publisher=[[WBOY-TV]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323183355/https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |archivedate=March 23, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Justice orders shutdown of non-essential businesses in West Virginia; first community-transmitted case has been confirmed |url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/gov-justice-orders-shutdown-of-non-essential-businesses-in-west/article_24910f48-6d21-11ea-8518-3fbb944964d3.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=West Virginia's News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, WV Statewide Day of Prayer, a 45-minute service dedicated to the people affected with Coronavirus disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvnstv.com/video/wv-statewide-day-of-prayer-service/4428831/|title=WV Statewide Day of Prayer Service|website=WVNS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> It was held by Governor Jim Justice and moderator Dr. Dan Anderson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.wv.gov/News/press-releases/2020/Pages/Gov.-Justice,-religious-leaders-to-hold-virtual-statewide-Day-of-Prayer-service-tomorrow-at-noon.aspx|title=Gov. Justice, religious leaders to hold virtual statewide Day of Prayer service tomorrow at noon.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal response ===\nWest Virginia will receive $5.6 million of federal money to fight COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/senators-west-virginia-to-receive-nearly-million-for-covid-/article_84856dbd-0431-5122-a3ef-cdcc2d33da0e.html Senators: West Virginia to receive nearly $5.6 million for COVID-19 response] WV News, March 17, 2020</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships|publisher= NCAA|date= March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title= NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak| publisher= MLive.com|date= March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19 Information] from the West Virginia Department of Health & Human Resources\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|United States|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Disasters in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Health in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:2020 in West Virginia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "add short description per WP:SHORT DESC", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_West_Virginia"}
